selves, open, in as far as they are not commanded, and allowable, in as far as they are not forbidden.

Some have held that there should not be Laws about things indif- ferent, but only about things either of a natural or a divine obligation3 —that laws should not create obligations, but declare them only.

But this is so far from being true, that Things Indifferent are the especial and proper matter of Human Laws. For what is com- manded by God, we are bound to d03 What is forbidden by God, we are bound not to d0; without the existence of Human Laws. Hence the peculiar field in which Human Laws can excrt their power of obliging, is Things Indifferent, when there was no pre-existing obli- gation.
